Here's how to save and restore draft text using .NET MAUI's app lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

```csharp
// NotePage.xaml.cs
public partial class NotePage : ContentPage
{
    private const string DraftKey = "note_draft_text";

    public NotePage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();

        // Subscribe to lifecycle events
        App.Current.Windows[0].Backgrounding += OnBackgrounding;
        App.Current.Windows[0].Resumed += OnResumed;

        // Restore any existing draft on page load
        RestoreDraft();
    }

    private void OnBackgrounding(object sender, BackgroundingEventArgs e)
    {
        SaveDraft();
    }

    private void OnResumed(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        RestoreDraft();
    }

    private void SaveDraft()
    {
        Preferences.Set(DraftKey, NoteEditor.Text ?? string.Empty);
    }

    private void RestoreDraft()
    {
        NoteEditor.Text = Preferences.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);
    }

    // Call this when the user explicitly saves/discards
    public void ClearDraft()
    {
        Preferences.Remove(DraftKey);
    }
}
```

```xml
<!-- NotePage.xaml -->
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             x:Class="YourApp.NotePage">
    <Editor x:Name="NoteEditor"
            Placeholder="Start typing your note..." />
</ContentPage>
```

**Key points:**

- **`Preferences`** persists small strings across app restarts — ideal for draft text.
- **`Backgrounding`** fires when the app loses focus (home button, app switch).
- **`Resumed`** fires when the app returns to the foreground.
- Call `ClearDraft()` after the user saves or discards the note so stale drafts don't reappear.

For larger text, consider writing to a file via `FileSystem.AppDataDirectory` instead of `Preferences`.
